{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}} {{Use British English|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox venue | name = Mount Vernon Sports Stadium | nickname = | image = | location = Daldowie Road, [[Mount Vernon]], [[Glasgow]], Scotland | coordinates = 55°50'31.0"N 4°07'23.9"W | opened = 1927 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = 1990 | owner = | operator = | surface = }}
'''Mount Vernon Sports Stadium''' was a former sports and greyhound racing stadium on Daldowie Road, [[Mount Vernon, Glasgow|Mount Vernon]], in the south-east of [[Glasgow]], Scotland.
The sports stadium was built on the site of the Daldowie Colliery on the south side of the [[Argyle Line|Argyle railway line]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.old-maps.co.uk/#/Map/267143/662998/12/100954|title=OS Plan 1956-1965|publisher=old-maps.co.uk}}</ref> after Andrew Beattie of Forest Street, [[Airdrie, North Lanarkshire|Airdrie]] gained planning permission from the Lanarkshire council in early 1927.<ref>{{cite book|last=Barnes|first=Julia|title=Daily Mirror Greyhound Fact File|page =294|year=1988|publisher=Ringpress Books|isbn=0-948955-15-5}}</ref>
The build cost over £3,500 and the stadium could accommodate 4,000 spectators. The greyhound racing was independent (unlicensed)<ref>{{cite book|last=Furby|first=R|title=Independent Greyhound Racing|page =85|year=1968|publisher=New Dominion House}}</ref> and the first race took place on 10 October 1927. Race distances included 260, 450, 620 and 815 yards. The track was a leading independent track and offered prize money levels that matched or surpassed many [[National Greyhound Racing Club]] licensed tracks.<ref>{{cite book|last=Barnes|first=Julia|title=Daily Mirror Greyhound Fact File|page =294|year=1988|publisher=Ringpress Books|isbn=0-948955-15-5}}</ref> The leading race events held at Mount Vernon were the Mount Vernon Derby and Mount Vernon St Leger.
The track closed in 1990 and was demolished in 2007 with the site now consisting of grassland sitting next door to a waste recycling centre and a dogs trust.
